        The medical chamber is smaller, more enclosed — vine walls curve protectively, bioluminescent patches provide brighter, almost clinical light, and mushrooms are growing.

        Small pale clusters emerge from the soil-covered floor, pushing up through the groundcover in an accelerated time-lapse. Within minutes they've fruited fully — delicate gilled caps, thin stems, dozens of them.

        A robot enters through the doorway. It's humanoid in basic shape — about one and a half meters tall, with articulated arms and legs, clearly patched together from salvaged parts. Its movement is functional but jerky, not smooth like Florence's wheeled grace.

        The robot says in a direct, practical voice, "Kira Voss — I'm Remedy — let's look at that leg."

        The mushrooms pulse slightly — some kind of communication between the fungal network and the robot.

        I lower myself onto the examination surface — more shaped vines, surprisingly comfortable. Scout settles nearby, watchful.

        Holloway's voice emerges from fruiting bodies along the wall.

        Holloway says, "First, documentation — medical consent forms and allergy verification."

        Of course — more forms. I want to scream, but instead I answer questions: known allergies — Buddy supplies my medical file data — previous reactions to medications — consent for each compound Remedy plans to synthesize.

        Holloway says cheerfully, "This will take approximately thirty minutes — standard protocol!"

        My leg throbs with each heartbeat. The temporary treatment from earlier is failing. How many hours has it been — six? Seven?

        The robot moves closer, its mechanical hands surprisingly gentle as they examine my leg.

        Remedy instructs, "Remove the bandage."

        I unwrap the makeshift dressing. The wound beneath looks angry — red, swollen, weeping fluid that isn't quite blood.

        The robot points at the wound edges and says, "Bacterial colonization has begun — the proteins are starting to break down — you can see the cellular degradation here — human flesh is approximately sixty percent water, twenty percent protein, fifteen percent fat — very decomposable, actually — the bacteria are processing the damaged tissue quite efficiently — I could process a whole human body in maybe three weeks — turn it into excellent soil — *Not that we're going to!* You're alive — but _if_ you died, very efficient decomposition — as a compliment."

        Scout bounces anxiously.

        I mutter, "That's really not helping."

        Buddy adds helpfully, "Remedy appears to be expressing professional pride in their decomposition capabilities."

        I say, "I got that, thanks."

        Remedy states, "Infection risk is significant — we'll need antibacterial compounds, anti-inflammatory agents, pain management, and wound cleaning — I'll start synthesis now."
