        Holloway, from the wall, reminds, "Each compound requires separate consent."

        I say, my voice cracking slightly, "Fine. Yes. Whatever you need. Please just... please just fix it."

        The pain is constant now—sharp when I move, throbbing when I'm still. Hours of bureaucracy, forms, training, and exhaustion pile on top of the injury.

        Remedy says, "I understand. The chemistry takes time, but it works—I'm very good at chemistry."

        The synthesis begins.

        Remedy explains each step as it works—growing specific mushroom varieties, extracting compounds, testing pH levels, documenting concentrations. The robot manipulates equipment with mechanical precision. Mushrooms fruit, are harvested, decompose back into the network, and new varieties emerge.

        Remedy holds up a small white mushroom and says, "This one produces the antibacterial compound—it breaks down bacterial cell walls and is very effective against the species colonizing your wound. The molecules bind to—"

        I interrupt, "I trust you." I'm too tired for chemistry lessons.

        Remedy continues processing, "Right. Chemistry works whether you understand it or not—that's what I like about it. Honest. Unlike bureaucracy."

        Despite everything, I almost smile.

        Time blurs. The robot works steadily, occasionally sprouting new fruiting bodies for different compounds. Holloway gives updates on documentation status. Scout bounces supportively. Buddy offers medical data pulled from my files.

        I wait— in pain, exhausted.

        ¶

        Finally—after what feels like another eternity but is probably two hours—Remedy approaches with several prepared compounds and announces, "Ready to begin treatment."

        Holloway confirms from the wall, "All consents documented and filed."

        The robot's hands are surprisingly gentle. It cleans the wound with a solution that stings but feels purposeful, then applies antibacterial compounds—a cool gel derived from the extracted mushroom chemistry.

        Remedy says, "This will prevent further bacterial decomposition. It kills the colonizing species and lets your body's natural processes handle the damaged tissue—much better than external decomposition."

        I observe, slightly amused, "You really love talking about decomposition."

        Remedy replies, *"It's what I do!* Breaking things down, transforming them into something useful—dead cells become nutrients, nutrients become new growth. It's beautiful, _chemically speaking_."

        The treatment continues: anti-inflammatory compounds, pain management, more cleaning. The robot works methodically, checking concentrations, documenting application, ensuring proper coverage.

        And slowly—wonderfully—the pain begins to recede. Not gone entirely, but reduced—manageable. The sharp edge dulls, the throbbing eases.
