        Remedy says — satisfied: "The compounds are working. Your inflammatory response is decreasing. The bacterial colonization is halted. Wound should heal properly now. Excellent chemistry."

        I say — quietly: "Thank you."

        Remedy replies: "Chemistry doesn't need thanks. It just works."

        Remedy adds — with a hint of pleasure: "Though I am glad you're not decomposing. Much better to have living humans than dead ones. Even if dead ones make very rich soil."

        Scout bounces.

        Fresh bandages are applied — soft material Remedy says comes from processed plant fibers — clean, sterile, properly secured.

        Remedy says: "You'll need to rest now. Let the compounds work, let your body heal. I'll fruit antibacterial mushrooms daily for wound care. Maybe a week until full recovery."

        I repeat the word: "Rest." It sounds impossibly good.

        Holloway announces via the wall fruiting bodies: "We've assigned you temporary quarters. Scout will show you the way!"

        Scout bounces toward another doorway immediately.

        I stand — my leg still hurts, but it's bearable now; I can walk without wanting to scream.

        The robot watches me and says: "Human bodies are remarkable, actually. Self-healing, adaptive. Much more interesting alive than dead. Though both are valid states, chemically."

        I say — dryly: "I'll try to stay in the alive state."

        The robot answers cheerfully: "Excellent plan! Much less decomposition involved."

        The quarters are small — another vine-formed chamber with soft groundcover, dim bioluminescence, surprisingly private. Scout bounces in circles, showing me the water source — a spring flowing through shaped vines — the waste facilities (I don't ask how those work with a fungal network everywhere) — and the sleeping space of soft moss and woven plant fibers.

        I sink down onto the sleeping surface.

        My whole body aches and my mind feels like static. I've been through a crash and injury, a walk through an alien forest, intake forms, four hours of workplace safety training, medical documentation, and treatment.

        One endless day on an alien planet with bureaucratic plants — and somehow, I've survived it.

        Scout presses against my hand gently — warm, solid, comforting.

        I whisper to the small plant: "Thank you — for everything."

        Scout bounces once, then settles nearby — keeping watch.

        The bioluminescence dims further, responding to my exhaustion.

        I close my eyes.

        They helped — it took forever, filtered through absurd procedures, involved workplace harassment policies and decomposition commentary, but they genuinely helped.

        I'm alive, treated, safe.

        For now, that's enough. Sleep pulls me down like gravity — I surrender to it gratefully.
